author: Elisa Carollo
description: From A.A. Murakami’s immersive U.S. debut to a Tomashi Jackson survey, the city's first-ever Art Week has inspired a series of must-see exhibitions across its leading arts institutions.
title: Five Museum Shows to See During Houston Art Week

author: Alexandra Tremayne-Pengelly
description: Expedia is ramping up investment outside America as the U.S. travel market cools.
title: Expedia CEO Ariane Gorin Bets on Global Markets as US Travel Demand Slows

author: The Editors
description: Alex Zhavoronkov, founder and CEO of Insilico Medicine, explores how A.I. is driving drug discovery breakthroughs—and transforming the way medicines are discovered, tested and delivered. Zhavoronkov shares his vision for “pharma superintelligence,” where A.I. not only supports but directs decision-making in drug development. When paired with rigorous clinical validation, generative models in biomedicine can compress years of research into months.
title: Insilico CEO Alex Zhavoronkov Shares His Vision for ‘Pharma Superintelligence’

author: The Editors
description: Winston Weinberg, founder and CEO of Harvey, is reimagining legal and professional services through A.I. By combining reasoning models, specialized workflows and scalable tools, Harvey aims to make knowledge work more meaningful. Serving over 500 customers and reaching $100 million in ARR, Weinberg’s approach prioritizes enterprise trust, client impact and preparing the next generation of professionals to thrive alongside intelligent systems.
title: Harvey CEO Winston Weinberg Is Fixing Law’s ‘Broken Apprentice System’

author: The Editors
description: Marco Argenti, Goldman Sachs’ CIO is shaping how one of Wall Street’s most powerful firms approaches generative and agentic A.I. Under his leadership, Goldman has rolled out the GS A.I. Platform and the firm-wide GS A.I. Assistant, giving employees secure access to LLMs at scale, while piloting advanced coding agents. From banker copilots to firm-wide adoption, Argenti’s highlights both the promise and the risks of deploying A.I. in one of the world’s most tightly regulated industries.
title: Goldman Sachs’ Marco Argenti On Why Early-Career Workers Are Key to AI Management

author: The Editors
description: Ray Kurzweil, computer scientist, inventor and futurist, sees A.I. as the next step in human evolution. Merging with intelligent machines, Kurzweil argues, will enhance human intelligence, creativity, humor and compassion. By 2032, he predicts, these advancements may allow humans to achieve “Longevity Escape Velocity,” gaining more life from scientific progress than they lose each year.
title: Ray Kurzweil: AI Is Not Hollywood’s Alien Invasion

author: The Editors
description: Reid Hoffman, co-founder of LinkedIn and board chair of Manas AI, is leveraging A.I. to transform healthcare and drug discovery. He recently led a $24.6 million seed funding round for Manas AI, a company using generative computational chemistry and proprietary A.I. systems to accelerate treatments for cancer and rare diseases. Hoffman emphasizes that widespread adoption, not investor hype, is driving A.I.’s impact, though he cautions that concentration of leading models could hinder entrepreneurial dynamism and broad-based innovation.
title: Reid Hoffman: Why AI’s Real Impact Comes From Users, Not Investor Hype

author: Liz Provencher
description: Every inch of this New York City bar was designed with music in mind.
title: Birds, a Bar Where Music Comes First, Lands in the West Village

author: The Editors
description: Tareq Amin is no stranger to transforming global infrastructure. After spearheading Rakuten’s Open RAN revolution in telecom, he now leads Saudi Arabia’s $600 billion A.I. bet as CEO of Humain. Amin argues that A.I. is not about apps or chatbots but the harder, less glamorous foundations of compute, data, energy and connectivity. Humain is moving at startup speed with sovereign resources, with global partnerships with Nvidia, Cisco and Groq becoming central to building what Amin calls “the world’s most open, scalable A.I. infrastructure.”
title: Humain CEO Tareq Amin: Infrastructure Beats Apps in the Race for AI Dominance

author: The Editors
description: From classrooms to city halls, Chowdhury argues that A.I. only works if humans keep control, test it rigorously and design with local realities in mind.
title: Dr. Rumman Chowdhury: Culturally Aware A.I. Starts With Local Realities

author: The Editors
description: Waabi founder and CEO Raquel Urtasun challenges the industry’s “bigger is better” approach to A.I., arguing that brute-force scaling of compute and models is unsustainable and ultimately ineffective. Waabi’s interpretable end-to-end A.I. represents a breakthrough for autonomous trucking, enabling safer, faster and more scalable deployment.
title: Inside Waabi CEO Raquel Urtasun’s Bid to Make Driverless Trucks a 2025 Reality

author: Rachel Curry
description: OpenAI’s latest study finds ChatGPT is shaping daily life more than work, with women users now in the majority.
title: OpenAI Study Uncovers 3 Surprises About How People Use ChatGPT

author: Juliet Izon
description: From an allergen-free bakery from one of the city’s top pastry chefs to a steakhouse inside Grand Central, these are the tables to snag in New York City this month.
title: The 13 Best Restaurants Opening in New York City in September

author: The Editors
description: While competitors chase flashy consumer demos with massive, resource-hungry models, Cohere has placed a contrarian bet on enterprise-focused A.I., reaching a $6.8 billion valuation and more than doubling revenue from $35 million to over $100 million between March and May alone.
title: Ivan Zhang On Building a $6.8B AI Company by Rejecting Tech’s ‘Bigger Is Better’ Obsession

author: The Editors
description: In this wide-ranging Q&A, Yoshua Bengio—pioneer of deep learning and founder of Mila, Quebec’s leading A.I. research institute—reflects on the rapid acceleration of artificial intelligence and the risks he believes are being overlooked. Bengio discusses why leaving A.I. development solely to private industry is a dangerous mistake, how OpenAI’s o1 model marked a turning point and why the rise of agentic systems raises the specter of misalignment and risk.
title: Yoshua Bengio On A.I. Risks, Model Breakthroughs and Canada’s Role

author: Alexandra Tremayne-Pengelly
description: Airbnb is doubling down on services, experiences, hotels and A.I. to accelerate growth.
title: Airbnb CEO Brian Chesky’s Turnaround Plan Takes a Page From Amazon’s Book

author: The Editors
description: John Deere is using A.I. to cut chemicals, boost yields and give farmers tools built for the field, not Silicon Valley.
title: John Deere CTO Jahmy Hindman Is Turning A.I. Into a Farmer’s Tool

author: Elisa Carollo
description: “Museums today are expected to be more than just places to look at art—they’re destinations where people spend time,” director Melissa McDonnell Luján tells Observer
title: How CAMH Is Helping Houston Overcome the Art World’s ‘Southern Blind Spot’

author: The Editors
description: In this Q&A, Quant CEO Chetan Dube reflects on the seismic shifts A.I. is bringing to work, society and the global economy. He discusses agentic A.I.'s rise could reshape how we define employment, the role of digital twins in a hybrid human-machine future and the urgent need for new policies like machine taxation and universal basic income to ensure technology serves humanity rather than displaces it.
title: Quant’s Chetan Dube Prepares for the Incoming Digital Tsunami

author: Elisa Carollo
description: “The potential of sculpture to reinforce first-hand physical experience excites me,” the artist told Observer. “My test for good sculpture is that you can’t think of the work without thinking of the place, and vice versa.”
title: Antony Gormley Reflects on Sculpture as an Inquiry into Being and Space

author: The Editors
description: In this Q&A, Grammarly CEO Shishir Mehrotra outlines why the company’s “A.I. superhighway” strategy sets it apart from tech giants like Microsoft and Google, how specialized agents can reshape productivity and why the future of work depends on humans orchestrating A.I. teams rather than being replaced by them.
title: Grammarly CEO Shishir Mehrotra Is Building an A.I. Superhighway

author: The Editors
description: Insitro's co-founder is betting on the fact that real progress in biotech requires more than clever algorithms.
title: Daphne Koller Wants to Fix Drug Discovery With A.I.—and Real Data
